Annotations — revisited and extended.

Annotations and reflection are the two ideas that, together, make Spring possible. We met the built in annotations earlier, like at sign Override, at sign Deprecated, and at sign Suppress Warnings. Now we go deeper. We will write our own annotation type, and we will learn the meta annotations that control where and when the annotation is visible.

To declare a custom annotation, you use the at sign interface keyword, followed by a name. So at sign interface Audited declares a new annotation type called Audited. Inside the body, you can declare attributes, which look like methods with no body and an optional default value. So String value default empty string is an attribute called value, with a default of an empty string. String array tags default empty array is an attribute called tags, with a default of an empty array.

Then you control the annotation with two meta annotations. At sign Target takes one or more element types and restricts where the annotation can be applied. The most common element types are TYPE, for classes and interfaces. METHOD, for methods. FIELD, for fields. PARAMETER, for method parameters. CONSTRUCTOR, for constructors. And several others. At sign Retention takes a retention policy that controls how long the annotation is kept. The three retention policies are SOURCE, CLASS, and RUNTIME. Source retention means the annotation is discarded at compile time. Only source level tools, like lint tools, see it. Class retention means the annotation is written to the class file but is not loaded into memory at runtime. This is the default. Runtime retention means the annotation is present at runtime and is readable via reflection.

Critical fact to memorise. If you forget at sign Retention with runtime policy on a custom annotation, reflection will not see it. This is one of the most common bugs when people first write framework style annotations. Always include at sign Retention with retention policy runtime if you intend the annotation to be read at runtime.
